ENTRY            M0668   20260120   20260226   20260226       M143
SUBENT        M0668001   20260120   20260226   20260226       M143
BIB                 14         49
TITLE      Photodisintegration of deuterium and Big Bang
           nucleosynthesis
AUTHOR     (K.Y.Hara,H.Utsunomiya,S.Goko,H.Akimune,T.Yamagata,
           M.Ohta,H.Toyokawa,K.Kudo,A.Uritani,Y.Shibata,
           Y.-W.Lui,H.Ohgaki)
REFERENCE  (J,PR/D,68,072001,2003)
           (J,NP/A,738,136,2004)
INSTITUTE  (2JPNKON,2JPNKTO,2JPNAIS,1USATAM)
FACILITY   (ESTRG,2JPNAIS) Electron storage ring TERAS at the
            National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and
            Technology (AIST).
INC-SOURCE (LCS) The laser Compton scattering (LCS) beam
            developed at the National Institute of Advanced
            Industrial Science and Technology (AIST).
DETECTOR   (PROPC)
METHOD     (RINGR) 16 3He proportional counters (Eurisys Mesures
            96NH45) embedded in a polyethylene moderator; two
            sets of eight counters are mounted in double
            concentric rings at 7 and 10 cm, respectively, from
            the beam axis.
SAMPLE     Heavy water filled a 4.0 cm long cylindrical
            container made of aluminium with 50-micron Mylar
            foils being entrance and exit windows. The purity of
            the heavy water was determined to be 97 (1)% with
            NMR spectrometer.
ANALYSIS   Direct measurement.
ERR-ANALYS (ERR-S) Statistical error
           (ERR-1) Systematic errors. The systematic uncertainty
            has three sources:
            - the neutron emission rate of 252Cf source used for
               neutron detection efficiency measurement (~ 5%),
            - the total flux of the LCS g-rays (~ 3%),
            - angular distribution of neutrons (~ 2%).
           The overall  systematic  uncertainty is 6.2%  after
            adding three sources in quadrature.
COMMENT    Photodisintegration cross sections were measured for
            deuterium with Laser-Compton scattering g-beams at
            seven energies near threshold. Combined with the
            preceding data, R(E) = Na SIG V for the p(n,gamma)D
            reaction is for the first time evaluated based on
            experimental data with 6% uncertainty in the energy
            region relevant to the Big Bang nucleosynthesis
            (BBN) The result confirms the theoretical evaluation
            on which the BBN in the precision era relies.
STATUS     (TABLE,,K.Y.Hara+,J,PR/D,68,072001,2003)
            Data from Table I.
HISTORY    (20050218C)
           (20260120A) Corrected by VV and SD: INC-SOURCE,
            ERR-ANALYS, STATUS.
ENDBIB              49
